'''David Ker''' (February 1758 &ndash; January 21, 1805) was the first presiding professor (equivalent of a modern-day [[university president]]) of the [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill|University of North Carolina]].

==Biography==
===Early life===
David Ker was born in February 1758 in [[Downpatrick]], [[Ireland]].<ref name="documenting">[http://docsouth.unc.edu/browse/bios/pn0000898_bio.html Documenting the American South: David Ker, February 1758-21 Jan. 1805]</ref><ref name="williamspowell">William S. Powell, ''Dictionary of North Carolina Biography'', Volume 3, H-K, pp. 353-354 [http://books.google.com.au/books?id=gejhoRgwLXwC&pg=PA353&lpg=PA353&dq=%22david+ker%22+%22north+carolina%22&source=bl&ots=SF0ONWtHMr&sig=z8qdkUUAQrH91-2nv1eAYVSNtkw&hl=en&sa=X&ei=-3RRVP7BLeSymAXSw4LYCw&ved=0CDwQ6AEwBQ#v=onepage&q=%22david%20ker%22%20%22north%20carolina%22&f=false]</ref> He was of Scottish origin.<ref name="documenting"/> He graduated from [[Trinity College, Dublin|Trinity College]] in [[Dublin]].<ref name="documenting"/><ref name="franklinecourt">Franklin E. Court, ''The Scottish Connection: The Rise of English Literary Study in Early America'', Syracuse, New York: Syracuse University Press, 2001, p. 100 [http://books.google.com.au/books?id=X-Nsu3GAzzUC&pg=PA100&lpg=PA100&dq=%22david+ker%22+%22north+carolina%22&source=bl&ots=mW6SwmnSNY&sig=8iaZHY-Fg4Bn76Z4LPaR2IX5tco&hl=en&sa=X&ei=-3RRVP7BLeSymAXSw4LYCw&ved=0CEEQ6AEwBw#v=onepage&q=%22david%20ker%22%20%22north%20carolina%22&f=false]</ref> He became a Presbyterian minister with the [[List of Irish Presbyteries|Temple Patrick Presbytery]].<ref name="documenting"/> He emigrated to the United States in the 1780s. Indeed, he was in [[Orange County, North Carolina]] by 1789.<ref name="documenting"/>

===Career===
In 1791, he served as a Presbyerian minister in [[Fayetteville, North Carolina]].<ref name="documenting"/> He was a schoolteacher on weekdays and gave sermons in the courthouse on Sundays.<ref name="documenting"/>

He moved to [[Chapel Hill, North Carolina]] in 1794, where he served as the first presiding professor (now known as university president) of the [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]].<ref name="documenting"/> He resigned two years later, in 1796, after clashing with the trustees and students.<ref name="documenting"/>

He moved to [[Lumberton, North Carolina]].<ref name="documenting"/> He served as the first president of an academy founded by [[John Willis (planter)|John Willis]], a Brigadier General in the [[American Revolutionary War]] who owned a large plantation in Lumberton, in the 1790s.<ref name="documenting"/> Meanwhile, he passed the Bar exam.<ref name="documenting"/>

He moved to [[Natchez, Mississippi]] with John Willis in 1800.<ref name="documenting"/> He established the first public school for women in the [[Mississippi Territory]].<ref name="documenting"/> His wife and daughters taught at the school.<ref name="documenting"/> Shortly after, he becae the Sheriff and Clerk of the Court of Adams County, Mississippi]].<ref name="documenting"/> Two years later, in 1802, he was made a Judge by President [[Thomas Jefferson]].<ref name="documenting"/>

===Personal life===
He married Mary Ker.<ref name="documenting"/> They had five children: 
*David Ker.<ref name="documenting"/> He died unmarried at the age of twenty-three.<ref name="documenting"/>
*[[John Ker (planter)|John Ker]].<ref name="documenting"/> He married Mary Baker Ker, the daughter of [[Joshua Baker]], the 22nd Governor of [[Louisiana]], and became a surgeon, planter and politician.
*Sarah Ker.<ref name="documenting"/> She married Mr Cowden.<ref name="documenting"/>
*Eliza Ker.<ref name="documenting"/> She married [[Rush Nutt]] of the [[Laurel Hill Plantation]].<ref name="documenting"/>
*Martha Ker.<ref name="documenting"/> She married married William Terry.<ref name="documenting"/>

===Death===
He died on January 21, 1805 in Natchez, Mississippi.<ref name="documenting"/>

==Legacy==
His widow burned all his papers.<ref name="documenting"/> His portrait, however, is preserved at the Southern Historical Collection of the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.<ref name="documenting"/>

